Predicting the Success of NFL Draftees

Holland Emery and Ryan Berger

Introduction¶

We wanted to see how the draft position of players in the NFL relates to their succesfulnes in the NFl. If you are drafted first are you really the best player drafted that year. The first thing that we had to do was collect stats about players in the NFL and draft information. Then we calculated the succesfulness of every player by year based on their stats. We then standardized the scores based on position, since the different positions have very different successes, the max kicker score is close to 1200 while the max QB score is 140. We then averaged all of the seasons of each player and added the offset for Pro-Bowl selections to create a standardized success for each player. The NFL is one of the largest entertainment industries in the United States earning over $8 Billion in revenue in the 2018 season. Teams are always trying to get the most out of draft picks and other resources so understanding the draft and the potential success of draft picks is extremely important to a teams success. Data Science is important to coaches and other executives of a team to maximize the impact that they have on the league. If you are unfamilier with the structure of the nfl draft and the positions of player here are some useful links to provide important information about the nfl.

How the NFL Draft Works

Collecting Data¶

To get started we first had to get a list of every player drafted in the nfl, we chose to cut the lower bound for the year at 1970 since before then the data collected is inconsistent at best. To do this we scraped the draft information from the NFL official website. The NFL website seperates drafts by year so we were able to collect only the data that we wanted to work with in an organized manner. Once we had every player drafted we then had to collect the stats for each individual player, we were able to use a large database of stats collected from kaggle. The statistical data was stored in csv files which we then converted to sql tables for ease of use. The stats collected included individual statistics for recieving, passing, rushing, kicking, and defensive plays broken apart by year and player. Once we had this data we had every player drafted and their corresponding carrer statistics. There isn't code for player statistic because the information was already neatly packaged in csv files. We also needed to collect the number of pro-bowls each player went to since that is an important indicator of the success of a player.

Code for scraping draft information¶

Since we stored all important data in sql databases most of the code involved in data collection and cleaning will be shown in markdown due to the fact that the files are large the code only needs to be run once to structure the data in a usable manner.

from bs4 import BeautifulSoup as bs
import pandas as pd
import sqlite3
import requests
from os import path
import re
import urllib

def scrape(url, year):

g = requests.get(url)
page = bs(g.content)
table = page.findAll('table')
draft = pd.read_html(str(table))
rounds = 1
returned = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['pick', 'team', 'player', 'position', 'college', 'year', 'round'])
for i in draft:
    result = i
    result.columns = ['pick', 'team', 'player', 'position', 'college']
    result['year'] = year
    result['round'] = rounds
    rounds += 1
    returned = returned.append(result)
return returned

if name == "main":
drafts = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['pick', 'team', 'player', 'position', 'college', 'year', 'round']) for year in range(1970,2016):
d = scrape('http://www.nfl.com/draft/history/fulldraft?season='+str(year)+'&round=round2#round2', year)
drafts = drafts.append(d)
drafts = drafts.reset_index()
conn = sqlite3.connect('Player.sqlite')
drafts.to_sql('DraftInfo', con=conn)

Pro-Bowl scraper¶

from bs4 import BeautifulSoup as bs
import pandas as pd
import sqlite3
import requests
from os import path
import re
import urllib

def scrape(url):

g = requests.get(url)<br/>
page = bs(g.content)<br/>
table = page.findAll('table')<br/>
draft = pd.read_html(str(table))<br/>
return draft<br/>

if name == "main":
drafts = pd.DataFrame()
for year in range(1970,2017):
d = scrape('https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/'+str(year)+'/probowl.htm')
drafts = drafts.append(d)
drafts = drafts.reset_index()
temp = drafts['Player']
count = pd.DataFrame()
players = {}
for i in temp:
i = i.replace('%','').replace('+','')
if i in players:
players[i] += 1
else:
players[i] = 1
results = pd.DataFrame(list(players.items()))
results.columns= ['Name','Count']
results['Name'] = results.apply(lambda x: x['Name'].split(' ')[1]+", "+x['Name'].split(' ')[0], axis=1)
conn = sqlite3.connect('Success.sqlite')
results.to_sql('ProBowl', con=conn)

Working with Data¶

After looking at the data we collected we realized that a majority of players were missing the position they played. This posed a problem since the position a player plays is important in the calculation of their success. to solve this we found a website that contains every player that has every played that has played in the NFL and their corresponding position. This data was scraped in a way that is similar to the draft information. Some players have nicknames that are more commonly used then their given names ie Mike and Michael so we created two tables of names and positions one with the given name and one with the last name and first two initials of their first name. We then determined which statistics are relavent for a player given whether they were an offensive, defensive, or special teams player.

from bs4 import BeautifulSoup as bs
import pandas as pd
import sqlite3
import requests
from os import path
import re
import string
import urllib

def scrape(url):
g = requests.get(url)
page = bs(g.content)
table = page.find(id='div_players')
lines = table.findAll('p')
players = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Name', 'Position', 'Start', 'End'])
for i in lines:
t=re.search('(.\n?)', str(i))
pos = t.group(0).replace('\n','').replace('(','').replace(')','')
n=re.search('\">.</a>',str(i)).group(0).replace('\">','').replace('</a>','')
temp = n.split(' ')
n = temp[1]+', '+temp[0][:2]
s=re.search('\d\d\d\d-', str(i)).group(0).replace('-','')
e=re.search('-\d\d\d\d',str(i)).group(0).replace('-','')
temp = pd.DataFrame({'Name':[n],'Position':[pos], 'Start':[s], 'End':[e]})
players = players.append(temp)
return players
if name == "main":
positions = pd.DataFrame()
for i in list(string.ascii_uppercase):
pos = scrape("https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/"+i+"/")
positions = positions.append(pos)
positions = positions.reset_index()
conn = sqlite3.connect('Success.sqlite')
positions.to_sql('PositionsFirst', con=conn)

Combining data and Measuring Success¶

Once we determied which statistics were relevant based on what kind of player you are we were able to calculate the success of a player based on the stats that are important to that player. So this mean for offensive play makers we looked at their receiving yards, rushing yards, touchdowns, and turnovers. The code for calculating success shown below is the same as the code we ran except we are not writing to an sql database.

Code for calculating success for quarterbacks¶

In [330]:
file = "Stats.sqlite"
conn = sqlite3.connect(file)
conn2 = sqlite3.connect("Success.sqlite")
query = """SELECT * FROM Career_Stats_Passing WHERE Year > 1969"""
query2 = """SELECT "Player Id", "Year", "Rushing Yards Per Game", "Rushing TDs" FROM Career_Stats_Rushing WHERE Year > 1969"""
query3 = """SELECT "Player ID", "Year", "Fumbles Lost" FROM Career_Stats_Fumbles WHERE Year > 1969"""
qbs = pd.read_sql(query, conn)
run = pd.read_sql(query2, conn)
lost = pd.read_sql(query3, conn)
qbs = pd.merge(qbs, run, how='left', on=['Player Id', 'Year'])
qbs = pd.merge(qbs, lost, how='left', on=['Player Id', 'Year'])
qbs = qbs.replace('--', '0')
qbs = qbs.fillna(0)
qbs['Success'] = qbs.apply(lambda x: float(x['Passer Rating']) + (0.25*float(x['Rushing Yards Per Game'])) 
    + (0 if float(x['Games Played'])==0 else (6*float(x['Rushing TDs'])/float(x['Games Played']))), axis=1)
qbs['Success'] = qbs.apply(lambda x: x['Success'] - (6*float(x['Fumbles Lost'])), axis=1)
qbs['Success'] = qbs.apply(lambda x: x['Success'] if float(x['Passes Attempted'])>30 and float(x['Games Played']>3) else 0, axis=1)
success = qbs[['Player Id','Name','Year','Position','Team','Success']].copy()
#success.to_sql('QuarterBacks', con=conn2)
success.head()

sqlite_file = "Stats.sqlite"
conn = sqlite3.connect(sqlite_file)
query = """SELECT * FROM Career_Stats_Rushing WHERE Year > 1969"""
query2 = """SELECT * FROM Career_Stats_Receiving WHERE Year > 1969"""
query3 = """SELECT * FROM Career_Stats_Kick_Return WHERE Year > 1969"""
query4 = """SELECT * FROM Career_Stats_Punt_Return Where Year > 1969"""
punt_stats = pd.read_sql(query4,conn)
kick_stats = pd.read_sql(query3,conn)
rushing_stats = pd.read_sql(query,conn)
receiving_stats = pd.read_sql(query2,conn)
combined_stats = pd.merge(rushing_stats,
                          receiving_stats,
                          left_on=["Player Id","Year","Name","Team"],
                          right_on=["Player Id","Year","Name","Team"],
                          how="outer"
                         )
combined_stats = combined_stats.replace("--",0)
combined_stats = combined_stats.fillna(0)
combined_stats["Total Fumbles"] = combined_stats.apply(lambda x: float(x["Fumbles_x"]) + float(x["Fumbles_y"]),axis=1)
combined_stats2 = pd.merge(combined_stats,
                          punt_stats,
                          left_on=["Player Id","Year","Name","Team"],
                          right_on=["Player Id","Year","Name","Team"],
                          how="outer"
                         )
combined_stats2 = combined_stats2.replace("--",0)
combined_stats2 = combined_stats2.fillna(0)
combined_stats2["Total Fumbles"] = combined_stats2.apply(lambda x: float(x["Total Fumbles"]) + float(x["Fumbles"]),axis=1)
combined_stats2=combined_stats2.drop(['Fumbles', 'Fumbles_x', 'Fumbles_y'], axis=1)
combined_stats3 = pd.merge(combined_stats2,
                          kick_stats,
                          left_on=["Player Id","Year","Name","Team"],
                          right_on=["Player Id","Year","Name","Team"],
                          how="outer"
                         )
combined_stats3 = combined_stats3.replace("--",0)
combined_stats3 = combined_stats3.fillna(0)
combined_stats3["Total Fumbles"] = combined_stats3.apply(lambda x: float(x["Total Fumbles"]) + float(x["Fumbles"]),axis=1) 
combined_stats3 = combined_stats3.drop(["Fumbles"],axis=1)                        
combined_stats3["Total TDs"] = combined_stats3.apply(lambda x: float(x["Receiving TDs"]) + float(x["Rushing TDs"]) + float(x["Returns for TDs_x"]) + float(x["Returns for TDs_y"]),axis=1)
combined_stats3["Total Yards Per Return"] = combined_stats3.apply(lambda x: (float(x["Yards Per Return_x"]) + float(x["Yards Per Return_y"]))/2,axis=1)
combined_stats3["Total Yards"] = combined_stats3.apply(lambda x: float(x["Rushing Yards Per Game"]) + float(x["Yards Per Game"]),axis=1)
combined_stats3["Games Played_x"]=combined_stats3["Games Played_x"].astype("float")
combined_stats3["Yards Per Carry"]=combined_stats3.apply(lambda x: 0 if float(x["Rushing Attempts"])<10 else float(x["Yards Per Carry"]),axis=1)
combined_stats3["Success"] = combined_stats3.apply(lambda x:float(x["Total Yards"])*.1+float(x["Total TDs"])*.4+float(x["Total Yards Per Return"])*.2-float(x["Total Fumbles"])*.75,axis=1)
#print(combined_stats3["Success"].max())
conn2 = sqlite3.connect("Success.sqlite")
success = combined_stats3[["Player Id","Name","Year","Team","Success"]]
#success.to_sql("Offense",con=conn2)   
success.head()

query = """SELECT "Player Id","Year", "Forced Fumbles", "Fumble Return TDs" FROM Career_Stats_Fumbles WHERE Year > 1969"""
fumble_stats = pd.read_sql(query,conn)
combined_stats = pd.merge(defense_stats,
                          fumble_stats,
                          left_on=["Player Id","Year"],
                          right_on=["Player Id","Year"],
                          how="left"
                         )
#print(combined_stats.columns)
combined_stats = combined_stats.replace("--",0)
combined_stats = combined_stats.fillna(0)
combined_stats["success"] = combined_stats.apply(lambda x: 0 if x["Games Played"]==0 else (float(x["Assisted Tackles"])*1+float(x["Solo Tackles"])*2+float(x["Sacks"])*3+float(x["Safties"])*6+float(x["Ints"])*5.25+float(x["Forced Fumbles"])*5.25+float(x["Fumble Return TDs"])*31.5+float(x["Ints for TDs"])*31.5)/float(x["Games Played"]),axis=1)

file = "Stats.sqlite"
conn = sqlite3.connect(file)
conn2 = sqlite3.connect("Success.sqlite")
query = "SELECT * FROM Career_Stats_Field_Goal_Kickers WHERE Year > 1969"
query2 = """Select "Player Id", "Year", "Out of Bounds Kickoffs", "Kickoffs", "Kickoff Yards" FROM Career_Stats_Kickoff WHERE Year > 1969"""
query3 = """SELECT "Player Id", "Year", "Net Punting Average", "Punts", "Punts Inside 20 Yard Line" FROM Career_Stats_Punting WHERE Year > 1969"""
fg = pd.read_sql(query, conn)
punt = pd.read_sql(query2, conn)
kick = pd.read_sql(query3, conn)
fg = pd.merge(fg, punt, left_on=['Player Id', 'Year'], right_on=['Player Id', 'Year'], how='left')
fg = pd.merge(fg, kick, left_on=['Player Id', 'Year'], right_on=['Player Id', 'Year'], how='left')
fg = fg.replace('--', '0')
fg = fg.fillna('0')
fg['Success'] = fg.apply(lambda x: float(x['Percentage of Extra Points Made'])+ (0 if int(x['FGs Attempted'])<16 else ((float(x['FG Percentage 20-29 Yards'])*1.5)+(float(x['FG Percentage 30-39 Yards'])*2)+(float(x['FG Percentage 40-49 Yards'])*2.5)+(float(x['FG Percentage 50+ Yards']))*3)), axis=1)
fg['Success'] = fg.apply(lambda x: x['Success'] + (.025*float(x['Kickoff Yards'].replace(',','')) * (0 if x['Kickoffs']=='0' else (1- (float(x['Out of Bounds Kickoffs'])/float(x['Kickoffs']))) )), axis=1)
fg['Success'] = fg.apply(lambda x: x['Success'] + (float(x['Net Punting Average']) * (0 if x['Punts']=='0' else ((float(x['Punts Inside 20 Yard Line'])/float(x['Punts']))) )), axis=1)
success = fg[['Player Id','Name','Year','Position','Team','Success']].copy()
#success.to_sql('Kickers', con=conn2)
success.head()

Entity Resolution¶

Since the position for each player was not consistent throughout the data collected we had to perform entity resolution in order the create workable data. We used the postition tables created to match each player to their position. We did this by first checking to see if their full given name was present in both the tables and if it was not we then checked their last name and first two initials. If neither was present we dropped that player, we did this after we calculated success since the position does not matter when calculating overall success all that matters is the statistics, the defensive players with offensive stats were later dropped from the offensive results. however we did need positions when we wanted to standardize success over each position.

Quarterback Entity Resolution¶

sqlite_file = "Success.sqlite"
conn = sqlite3.connect(sqlite_file)
offenseQuery = """SELECT * FROM QuarterBacks"""
offense = pd.read_sql(offenseQuery,conn)
positionQuery = """SELECT * FROM Positions"""
position = pd.read_sql(positionQuery,conn)
c = conn.cursor()
for i in range(len(offense)):
    temp = offense.at[i,"Name"]
    pos = c.execute("""SELECT "Position" from Positions WHERE "Name" LIKE ?""",(temp,))
    test = pos.fetchone()
    if test == None:
        temp2 = temp.split(", ")
        temp3 = temp2[0]+", "+temp2[1][:2]
        pos2 = c.execute("""SELECT "Position" from PositionsFirst WHERE "Name" LIKE ?""",(temp3,))
        offense.at[i,"Position"] = pos2.fetchone()
        #print(temp)
    else:
        offense.at[i,"Position"] = test
    #print(pos.fetchone())
    #print(type(pos.fetchone())) 
offense = offense.mask(offense.eq('None')).dropna()
offense["Position"] = offense.apply(lambda x: "QB",axis=1)
#offense.to_sql("QB Position",con=conn)
offense.head()

Standardization¶

For each group of players ie. offense, defense, ect. we needed to determine which position a player plays if they are listed as playing multiple we did this by selecting which of the possible positions is the most likely candidate and using that as the players position. We then standardized the results to a max of 100 for each position. This way way we were only comparing the success of each player given their position. we do this because success varies between position and we only wanted to compare players with other players that have same position. We then included the offset for pro-bowls.

query = """SELECT * FROM 'Offense Position'"""
conn = sqlite3.connect("Success.sqlite")

offense = pd.read_sql(query, conn)
offense['Position'] = offense['Position'].apply(lambda x: 'WR' if 'wr' in x.lower() else x)
offense['Position'] = offense['Position'].apply(lambda x: 'RB' if 'rb' in x.lower() else x)
offense['Position'] = offense['Position'].apply(lambda x: 'FB' if 'fb' in x.lower() else x)
offense['Position'] = offense['Position'].apply(lambda x: 'TE' if 'te' in x.lower() else x)
offense['multi'] = offense['Position'].apply(lambda x: x=='WR' or x=='RB' or x=='FB' or x=='TE')
offense = offense[offense.multi]
names.extend(offense['Name'].tolist())
test = offense.groupby('Position').max()
offense['standard'] = offense.apply(lambda x: (100*x['Success']/test['Success'][x['Position']]+(2*pb[x['Name']] if x['Name'] in pb else 0)), axis=1)
temp = offense.groupby('Name')['Position']
temp = temp.apply(lambda x: x.values[0])
offense = offense.groupby('Name').mean()
offense['Position'] = temp
print(offense.sort_values(by='standard', ascending=False).head(20)[['standard','Position']])

Standardization for Offesnsive Line¶

Offensive Linebackers don't have stats to base success off of, if they are doing what they are supposed to they are making sure nothing happens, the only stats are sacks allowed and penalty yards, neither of which are well recorded especially going back 20+ years. But the Offensive Linebackers are some of the most important player on the field, if a team does not have a good OLine then they will not do well so we couldn't ignore OLine players. Since Offensive Linebackers dont have good stats to base success off of we choose to rank success based on how many pro bowls that player went to since only the best players in any given year are selected to go to the probowl.

In [131]:
queryOL = """SELECT * FROM Positions"""
connOL = sqlite3.connect("Success.sqlite")

OLine['Position'] = OLine['Position'].apply(lambda x: 'OT' if 't' in x.lower() and 'te' not in x.lower() else x)

OLine['Position'] = OLine['Position'].apply(lambda x: 'OG' if 'g' in x.lower() else x)
OLine['Position'] = OLine['Position'].apply(lambda x: 'OLB' if 'olb' in x.lower() else x)

OLine = OLine[OLine.multi]
OLine = OLine[OLine.duplicate]

maximum = OLine['score'].max()
OLine = OLine.groupby('Name').max()
test = OLine.groupby('Position').max()

temp = OLine.groupby('Name')['Position']
temp = temp.apply(lambda x: x.values[0])
OLine = OLine.groupby('Name').mean()
OLine['Position'] = temp
OLine = OLine.drop(['duplicate'],axis=1)

We decided to test our regression on arguable the best Quarterback to every play, Tom Brady, he was drafted extremely low considering how good he ended up being. He was drafted 199th overall and our regression model says that he should have a score of 21.9 which is much lower than his actual score of 75.5.

residuals = pd.DataFrame()
residuals['pick'] = draftdrop['pick']
residuals['predict'] = model.predict(draftdrop)
residuals['success'] = draftdrop['success']
residuals['residual'] = residuals.apply(lambda x: x['success']-x['predict'], axis=1)
residuals['position'] = draftdrop['position']

Our model will predict a players success based on their draft number and position. The value predicted is far from perfect but we have shown that on average players drafted earlier in the draft are better than ones drafted later. Excluding a few outliers such as Tom Brady who has outperformed almost everyones expectations. looking at the residuals a player is more likely to be much more succesful than predicted while it is far less likely for them be less successful. This is likely due to the fact that players drafted often never play at a high level in the nfl causing our model to show low averages. many players play a few games before being cut from a team or released due to injury.
